@node Overview
@chapter Overview

Infovore is an AI-powered content aggregator and curator that runs @*
entirely inside Emacs.  It fetches content from user-configured sources @*
--- Twitter accounts, RSS feeds, Substack newsletters --- stores @*
everything in a local SQLite database, uses an AI model (via @samp{gptel}) to @*
score each item for relevance against a natural-language interest @*
profile, and presents the curated results in an elfeed-style split-pane @*
interface. @*

The package solves the problem of information overload: rather than @*
manually checking dozens of feeds and accounts, you describe your @*
interests once, and infovore continuously fetches, evaluates, and @*
surfaces only the content that matters to you.  Items that score above a @*
configurable relevance threshold appear in the feed list; everything @*
else is stored but hidden from the default view. @*

Infovore is organized around several cooperating modules: @*

@itemize
@item
@strong{Source plugins} fetch content asynchronously from different platforms. @*
Each source type (RSS, Twitter, Substack) is implemented as an EIEIO @*
class inheriting from an abstract base class defined in @*
@samp{infovore-source.el}.  New source types can be added by subclassing @*
and implementing two generic methods. @*

@item
@strong{Database layer} (@samp{infovore-db.el}) manages all persistence through @*
@samp{emacsql}.  It stores fetched items, tracks @*
read/starred/curated state, and maintains a daily token budget ledger. @*

@item
@strong{AI curation} (@samp{infovore-ai.el}) handles the scoring pipeline.  For @*
each uncurated item, it constructs a prompt containing the user's @*
interest profile and the item's content, sends it to the configured @*
@samp{gptel} backend, parses the JSON response to extract a relevance score @*
and a summary, and updates the database.  A daily token budget @*
prevents runaway API costs. @*

@item
@strong{Feed list view} (@samp{infovore-list.el}) displays curated items in a @*
@samp{tabulated-list-mode} buffer with columns for source type, author, @*
title, score, and relative timestamp. @*

@item
@strong{Item detail view} (@samp{infovore-show.el}) renders either the AI-generated @*
summary or the original content (with HTML rendered via @samp{shr}) in a @*
split buffer below the feed list. @*

@item
@strong{Mode line indicator} (@samp{infovore-modeline.el}) shows the count of @*
unread curated items as @samp{[IV:N]} in the global mode line. @*

@item
@strong{Ebib integration} (@samp{infovore-ebib.el}) is an optional module that @*
lets you save an item's citation metadata to an @samp{ebib} bibliography @*
database via @samp{zotra}. @*
@end itemize

The core dependencies are @samp{gptel} (AI backend), @samp{elfeed} (XML parsing @*
only), @samp{emacsql} (database), and Emacs 29.1 or @*
later (for native @samp{libxml} support and @samp{shr}). @*

