@node Sources configuration
@section Sources configuration

@vindex infovore-sources
The user option @code{infovore-sources} defines the list of content sources @*
that infovore monitors.  Each element is a property list with at least a @*
@code{:type} key specifying the source type (@code{rss}, @code{twitter}, or @code{substack}) @*
and type-specific keys providing the necessary identifiers. @*

The default value is an empty list.  The accepted type is a list of @*
plists.  You must populate this variable for infovore to have anything @*
to fetch.  A typical configuration looks like this: @*

@lisp
(setq infovore-sources
      '((:type rss :url "https://example.com/feed.xml")
        (:type twitter :username "elikiln")
        (:type substack :publication "astralcodexten")))
@end lisp

Each source type requires different keys: @*

@itemize
@item
@code{rss} --- requires @code{:url} (the feed URL). @*
@item
@code{twitter} --- requires @code{:username} (without the @samp{@@} prefix). @*
@item
@code{substack} --- requires @code{:publication} (the subdomain name, e.g. @*
@samp{"astralcodexten"} for @samp{astralcodexten.substack.com}). @*
@end itemize

All types accept an optional @code{:name} key for a custom display name; @*
otherwise the name is derived from the identifier. @*

@node AI curation settings
@section AI curation settings

@vindex infovore-interest-profile
@vindex infovore-relevance-threshold
@vindex infovore-daily-token-budget
@vindex infovore-budget-reset-hour
The user option @code{infovore-interest-profile} is a free-form string @*
describing your interests in natural language.  This string is included @*
verbatim in every AI scoring prompt, so the more specific and @*
descriptive it is, the better the AI can judge relevance.  The default @*
value is an empty string.  When left empty, AI scoring is skipped @*
entirely and items remain uncurated.  A good profile might look like: @*

@lisp
(setq infovore-interest-profile
      "AI safety, Emacs, functional programming, philosophy of mind,
       effective altruism, longevity research")
@end lisp

The user option @code{infovore-relevance-threshold} sets the minimum AI score @*
(a float between 0.0 and 1.0) for an item to appear in the default @*
curated feed view.  The default value is @code{0.5}.  Lowering this value @*
shows more items at the cost of including less relevant content; @*
raising it produces a tighter, more selective feed.  This threshold is @*
used by @code{infovore-list-refresh} when filtering items @*
(@ref{Refreshing and filtering}). @*

The user option @code{infovore-daily-token-budget} caps the estimated number @*
of tokens that infovore will consume per day for AI curation.  The @*
default value is @code{100000}.  Token usage is estimated heuristically (one @*
token per four characters) and tracked both in memory and in the @*
database.  When the budget is exhausted, remaining uncurated items are @*
deferred to the next budget period.  You would increase this value if @*
you have many sources and want more items scored per day, or decrease it @*
to control API costs. @*

The user option @code{infovore-budget-reset-hour} specifies the hour of the @*
day (0--23) at which the daily token budget resets.  The default value is @*
@code{0} (midnight).  If you typically use Emacs late at night, setting this @*
to a later hour (e.g. @code{4}) ensures your budget period aligns with your @*
usage pattern rather than resetting mid-session. @*

@node Twitter backend settings
@section Twitter backend settings

@vindex infovore-twitter-backend
@vindex infovore-twitter-rss-bridge-url
@vindex infovore-twitter-api-bearer-token
@vindex infovore-twitter-scraper-command
The user option @code{infovore-twitter-backend} selects which method infovore @*
uses to fetch tweets.  It accepts one of three symbols: @*

@itemize
@item
@code{rss-bridge} (the default) --- fetches tweets as an Atom feed from a @*
self-hosted RSS-Bridge instance.  This is the recommended approach. @*
@item
@code{api} --- uses the official Twitter API v2 with a bearer token. @*
@item
@code{scraper} --- shells out to an external command-line tool. @*
@end itemize

The user option @code{infovore-twitter-rss-bridge-url} specifies the base URL @*
of your RSS-Bridge instance (e.g. @*
@samp{"https://rss-bridge.example.com"}).  It is required when @*
@code{infovore-twitter-backend} is set to @code{rss-bridge}.  The default value is @*
@code{nil}. @*

The user option @code{infovore-twitter-api-bearer-token} holds the bearer @*
token for the official Twitter API v2.  It is required when @*
@code{infovore-twitter-backend} is set to @code{api}.  The default value is @code{nil}. @*
You obtain this token from the Twitter Developer Portal. @*

The user option @code{infovore-twitter-scraper-command} specifies the @*
executable name or path of an external tweet scraper.  It is required @*
when @code{infovore-twitter-backend} is set to @code{scraper}.  The default value @*
is @code{nil}.  The command is called with the Twitter username as its sole @*
argument and must write a JSON array of tweet objects to standard output. @*
Each object should contain at least @code{id}, @code{text}, @code{created_at}, and @*
@code{url} keys. @*

@node Scheduling settings
@section Scheduling settings

@vindex infovore-fetch-interval
The user option @code{infovore-fetch-interval} controls how many minutes @*
elapse between automatic fetch cycles.  The default value is @code{60}.  The @*
type is an integer.  A lower value means more frequent fetching (and @*
potentially more API usage); a higher value reduces resource @*
consumption.  This option takes effect when @code{infovore-start} is called @*
(@ref{Starting and stopping}). @*

@node Database settings
@section Database settings

@vindex infovore-database-file
The user option @code{infovore-database-file} specifies the path to the @*
SQLite database file.  The default value is @samp{infovore.db} inside @*
@code{user-emacs-directory}.  The type is a file path.  You might change this @*
if you want the database stored on a different disk or outside your @*
Emacs configuration directory.  The database is created automatically on @*
first use. @*

@node Error handling settings
@section Error handling settings

@vindex infovore-max-retries
@vindex infovore-retry-base-delay
The user option @code{infovore-max-retries} sets the maximum number of retry @*
attempts when a fetch request fails.  The default value is @code{3}.  The @*
type is an integer.  After all retries are exhausted, the source is @*
skipped for the current fetch cycle and the failure is logged. @*

The user option @code{infovore-retry-base-delay} sets the base delay in @*
seconds for exponential backoff between retries.  The default value is @*
@code{30}.  The delay for attempt @emph{N} is calculated as @code{(* base-delay (expt
4 N))}, yielding intervals of 30 seconds, 120 seconds, and 480 seconds @*
with the default base delay.  You would increase this if your sources @*
are rate-limited and need longer cool-down periods. @*

@node Feed list display settings
@section Feed list display settings

@vindex infovore-list-format
The user option @code{infovore-list-format} controls the columns displayed in @*
the feed list buffer.  Each element is a list of @code{(FIELD WIDTH
SORTABLE-P)}.  The default value is: @*

@lisp
'((:source 6 t) (:author 20 t) (:title 0 t) (:score 5 t) (:time 12 t))
@end lisp

Available fields are @code{:source} (type icon), @code{:author}, @code{:title}, @*
@code{:score} (relevance), and @code{:time} (relative timestamp).  A width of @code{0} @*
means the column expands to fill available space.  You can reorder, @*
remove, or resize columns to suit your workflow. @*

