@node Database management
@section Database management

@findex infovore-db-ensure
@findex infovore-db-close
The function @code{infovore-db-ensure} opens the database connection if it is @*
not already open and creates the required tables and indexes if they do @*
not exist.  It returns the active @samp{emacsql} connection object.  This @*
function is called automatically by most other database functions and by @*
@code{infovore} and @code{infovore-start}, so you rarely need to call it directly. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-close} closes the database connection if it is @*
open.  You might call this if you need to move or replace the database @*
file while Emacs is running. @*

@node Item storage and retrieval
@section Item storage and retrieval

@findex infovore-db-insert-item
@findex infovore-db-update-item
@findex infovore-db-get-item
@findex infovore-db-item-exists-p
@findex infovore-db-query-items
@findex infovore-db-uncurated-items
@findex infovore-db-count-unread-curated
The function @code{infovore-db-insert-item} inserts an @code{infovore-item} struct @*
into the database.  It uses @samp{INSERT OR IGNORE} semantics, so attempting @*
to insert an item with a duplicate ID is silently skipped.  This is the @*
mechanism behind infovore's URL-based deduplication. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-update-item} updates specific fields of an @*
existing item identified by its ID@.  It accepts a plist of field-value @*
pairs (e.g. @code{:score 0.8 :summary "..."}).  Boolean fields (@code{:read-p}, @*
@code{:starred-p}, @code{:curated-p}) are automatically converted to integers for @*
storage. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-get-item} retrieves a single item by ID and @*
returns it as an @code{infovore-item} struct, or @code{nil} if not found. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-item-exists-p} returns non-nil if an item with @*
the given ID exists in the database.  This is used during fetch cycles @*
to skip already-known items without loading their full content. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-query-items} is the general-purpose query @*
function.  It accepts keyword arguments for filtering: @code{:curated-only}, @*
@code{:min-score}, @code{:source-id}, @code{:source-type}, @code{:limit}, @code{:offset}, and @*
@code{:order-by}.  It returns a list of @code{infovore-item} structs.  The feed @*
list view uses this function to populate its display @*
(@ref{Refreshing and filtering}). @*

The function @code{infovore-db-uncurated-items} returns items where @*
@code{curated} is false, ordered by fetch time (oldest first).  It accepts an @*
optional @code{limit} argument.  The AI curation pipeline uses this function @*
to find items that need scoring @*
(@ref{AI scoring pipeline}). @*

The function @code{infovore-db-count-unread-curated} returns the count of @*
items that are both curated and unread.  The mode line indicator uses @*
this to display the unread count @*
(@ref{Mode line indicator}). @*

@node Token budget tracking
@section Token budget tracking

@findex infovore-db-get-budget-tokens
@findex infovore-db-add-budget-tokens
@findex infovore-ai-budget-exhausted-p
The function @code{infovore-db-get-budget-tokens} returns the number of @*
tokens used on a given date (specified as a @samp{"YYYY-MM-DD"} string).  It @*
returns @code{0} if no entry exists for that date. @*

The function @code{infovore-db-add-budget-tokens} adds a token count to the @*
budget for a given date.  It uses upsert semantics: if no row exists for @*
the date, one is created; otherwise the amount is added to the existing @*
total. @*

The function @code{infovore-ai-budget-exhausted-p} returns non-nil when the @*
daily token budget has been fully consumed.  The curation pipeline @*
checks this before scoring each item and stops early when it returns @*
non-nil (@ref{AI curation settings}). @*

@node AI scoring pipeline
@section AI scoring pipeline

@findex infovore-ai-score-item
@findex infovore-ai-curate-pending
The function @code{infovore-ai-score-item} scores a single @code{infovore-item} @*
asynchronously using @samp{gptel}.  It constructs a prompt from the user's @*
interest profile and the item's content, sends it to the AI backend, and @*
calls a callback with a cons cell @code{(score . summary)} on success, or @*
@code{nil} on failure.  Scoring is skipped (callback called with @code{nil}) in @*
three cases: the interest profile is empty, the daily token budget is @*
exhausted, or the item has neither title nor content.  Content longer @*
than 4000 characters is truncated before being sent. @*

The function @code{infovore-ai-curate-pending} processes all uncurated items @*
sequentially.  For each item, it calls @code{infovore-ai-score-item}, and @*
on success updates the item's score, summary, and curated status in the @*
database.  Processing stops early if the token budget is exhausted. @*
When all items have been processed (or the budget runs out), it calls a @*
callback with the count of items successfully scored.  The main fetch @*
cycle calls this function after inserting newly fetched items @*
(@ref{Manual fetching}). @*

@node URL normalization and deduplication
@section URL normalization and deduplication

@findex infovore-normalize-url
The function @code{infovore-normalize-url} normalizes a URL for @*
deduplication purposes.  It lowercases the scheme and host, strips @*
trailing slashes from the path, removes @samp{utm_*} tracking query @*
parameters, and preserves fragments.  The normalized URL serves as the @*
item's unique ID in the database, ensuring that the same article reached @*
via different tracking links is not stored twice. @*

@node Logging
@section Logging

@findex infovore-log
@vindex infovore-log-buffer-name
The function @code{infovore-log} writes a timestamped, level-tagged message to @*
the @samp{*infovore-log*} buffer.  The level argument is one of @code{info}, @*
@code{warn}, or @code{error}.  All significant events throughout infovore --- @*
fetch attempts, parse results, AI scoring, budget exhaustion, errors --- @*
are logged through this function.  The log buffer is useful for @*
diagnosing fetch failures, understanding why items were skipped, and @*
monitoring token usage. @*

The variable @code{infovore-log-buffer-name} holds the name of the log @*
buffer.  Its default value is @samp{"*infovore-log*"}. @*

@node Fetch with retry
@section Fetch with retry

@findex infovore-fetch-with-retry
The function @code{infovore-fetch-with-retry} fetches a URL asynchronously @*
with exponential backoff retry.  On success, it calls the callback with @*
the response buffer.  On final failure (after all retries), it calls @*
the callback with @code{nil}.  The number of retries defaults to @*
@code{infovore-max-retries} (@ref{Error handling settings}).  All source plugins use @*
this function for their HTTP requests, providing uniform retry behavior @*
across the package. @*

@node Source protocol
@section Source protocol

@findex infovore-source-fetch
@findex infovore-source-parse
The generic function @code{infovore-source-fetch} is the entry point for @*
fetching new items from a source.  It takes a source object and a @*
callback, and calls the callback asynchronously with a list of @*
@code{infovore-item} structs (or @code{nil} on failure).  Each source type @*
provides its own implementation of this method. @*

The generic function @code{infovore-source-parse} converts raw fetched data @*
(typically an XML parse tree or JSON alist) into a list of @*
@code{infovore-item} structs.  This is called internally by each source's @*
@code{infovore-source-fetch} implementation. @*

@node Ebib integration
@chapter Ebib integration

@findex infovore-ebib-save
@findex infovore-ebib-available-p
The optional module @samp{infovore-ebib.el} integrates infovore with @samp{ebib} @*
(the Emacs Bib@TeX{} database manager) and @samp{zotra} (a citation metadata @*
fetcher).  When both packages are installed, you can save an item's @*
bibliographic metadata directly to your @samp{ebib} database. @*

The command @code{infovore-ebib-save}, bound to @samp{S} in both @*
@code{infovore-list-mode} and @code{infovore-show-mode}, extracts the URL of the @*
item at point, passes it to @code{zotra-get-entry-from-url} to retrieve a @*
Bib@TeX{} entry, and imports the result into @samp{ebib} via @*
@code{ebib-import-entries}.  A confirmation message is displayed on success. @*

If either @samp{zotra} or @samp{ebib} is not installed, the command signals a @*
@code{user-error} explaining which package is missing.  The function @*
@code{infovore-ebib-available-p} returns non-nil when both packages are @*
loaded, which can be useful for conditionally binding keys or enabling @*
menu entries. @*

This module is loaded via @code{(require 'infovore-ebib nil t)} in the main @*
entry point, so it is silently skipped when its dependencies are absent. @*

